servings: 2
---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat #oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @red onion{1}(thinly sliced); dice remaining onion. Zest and quarter @lime{1} (for 4 servings, zest one lime and quarter both). Halve @long green pepper{2} lengthwise; remove stems and seeds. Dice @tomato{1} and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

In a #small microwave-safe bowl{}, combine sliced onion, juice from half the lime, @sugar{1/4%tsp} (1/2 tsp for 4), and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Microwave until onion is bright pink, ~{30%seconds}. Set aside to pickle.

In a #small pot{}, combine @jasmine rice{1/2%cup}, 3/4 cup water (1 1/2 cups for 4 servings), @southwest spice blend{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4), and a big pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. (You'll use the rest of the Southwest Spice Blend in Step 5.)

Keep covered off heat until ready to use in Step 5.

While rice cooks, place green peppers on a #baking sheet{} and rub all over with a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%tsp}. Season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}, then arrange cut sides down.

Roast on top rack until browned and softened, ~{15-18%minutes}.

In a #second small bowl{}, combine @guacamole{4%tbsp}, @sour cream{1.5%tbsp}, and a pinch of lime zest. Season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Set aside.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add diced onion and a pinch of @salt{pinch}; cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly browned, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in @black beans{1} and their liquid, @tex-mex paste{1}, and remaining @southwest spice blend{1%tbsp}. Bring to a simmer; cook until liquid is absorbed and beans are softened, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Fluff rice with a #fork{} and stir in remaining lime zest and @butter{1%tbsp} (2 TBSP for 4 servings). Stir into bean mixture; taste and season with @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

Once green peppers are done roasting, remove sheet from oven. Carefully stuff with about half the filling (save the rest for serving). Evenly sprinkle with @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}.

Return to top rack; bake until cheese melts, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Divide remaining filling between plates. Top with stuffed peppers, creamy guac, tomato, and as much pickled onion (draining first) as you like. Finish with a squeeze of lime juice. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Mildly spicy, sweet, and perfect for stuffing, green peppers are one of our favorite ingredients in quick (and tasty!) dinners. Speaking of stuffing, we combined lime-kissed, Southwest-spiced black beans with fluffy aromatic jasmine rice for a vegetarian twist on a meaty original. The peppers get a big sprinkle of Mexican cheeses that turn ooey-gooey as they bake and then they're topped with tomatoes, dollops of creamy guac, and tangy pickled onion.